<a class=MsoNormal><a target="_blank" href="http://pub6.ezboard.com/bnamelesstavern">The Nameless</a></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#cccccc><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/usenadorsurinami.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Senador Surinami</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_lightning.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Monk</span><br>  Posts: 167<br> <font color=#8b1a1a>(10/16/02 8:24:35 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fmonklybusiness43508frm17.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=288.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: ..</span><hr size=1> I had posted about this earlier. I do think its all a moot point now but I certainly think a lot of the current confusion would have been avoided if AC was separated between avoidance and mitigation.<br>
<br>
Furthermore, I think ATK should be broken down to two numbers. ATK should be split between accuracy and impact.<br>
<br>
In this way, a hit on a target would be based on the comparison between an attacker's accuracy skill and the defender's avoidance skill. The damage taken would be determined by the attacker's impact skill vs. the defender's mitigation skill.<br>
<br>
The next step would be how each class values each of these numbers. Because of this there would be modifier tables that adjust the four factors based upon a players class and race (and possibly AA skills too.) What this means is the true function of if a defender would be able to avoid a hit is based upon their raw avoidance skill, their class, their level, any AA mods, and the attacker's raw accuracy skill, their class, their level, any AA mods (for PvP)<br>
<br>
This means all that evil ALL/ALL equipment out there.... would have AC and ATK values split. A shield might have ONLY mitigation and no (or negative) avoidance since the idea with a shield is to block an attack rather than avoid it. But a warrior gets a HIGH modifier to mitigation skills while a monk gets a LOW modifier. The inverse is true for avoidance and therefore monks could CARE LESS about mitigation AC and focus on avoidance AC items since they get the most benefit off those items.<br>
<br>
Barbed Dragonscale boots? They have mediocre AC right now for a warrior but incredible AC for a monk. If Shiverback boots were ALL avoidance AC and Barbed Dragonscale boots were ALL mitigation AC, then suddenly monks might consider staying within their class specific armor for the best benefit.<br>
<br>
But it is all a moot point. This would have needed to have been implemented upon game's release to be useful today. My only hope is that some developer of a future game reads this kind of info and implements it to a proper use. <p><center><b>Senador Surinami of the Celestial Fists</b>
