</center></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#778899><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/bmonklybusiness43508.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=sleeka>Sleeka</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Young Grasshoppah</span><br>  Posts: 3<br> <font color=#8b1a1a>(10/16/02 9:16:36 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fmonklybusiness43508frm17.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=288.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Obfuscation</span><hr size=1> I always thought that they combined the AC numbers because they _wanted_ to confuse us.  I.e. Make it more difficult to figure out how the game works.<br>
<br>
If they wanted us _not_ to be confused, I think they would:<br>
<br>
A.  Clearly show all relevant parameters.<br>
B.  Provide detailed explanations of how the parameters should work.<br>
<br>
Before combining, they could have said: more mitigation  = the less damage per hit.  More avoidance = get hit less.  Now, it's:  well, take off all your eq, and see what your AC is naked.  Now, examine every piece of eq you're wearing and add up all the AC values. Now...<br>
<br>
The suggestion that having them combined makes it less confusing seem pretty ridiculous.<br>
<br>
